Background information

My data set is a RTMS (Response Time Measurement System) timer data from a health care software solution. The RTMS timer data was produced from actual user interacting with software user interface when background service collect data at real time. User timer measures actual the response time. This is also the time between user click on a button sends a request until the response come back. Each timer also contains additional information from a single transaction such as timer name, domain name, application name, user name, node name, end date time.

Why

Using timer data, I want to understand the following questions:

  • What is this softwares user profile groups?
  • What is the typical workflow? Find strong rules such as user action 1 leads to user action 2.
  • What are reasons causing system slow response time?

These questions would help software developers to understand actual user profiles and workflows, improve user experiences.

Data

The dataset contains a 1,000,000 rows and 24 columns of tiemr data and a week worth of data from the week of April 24th.

Supervised Learning

1. Hierarchical clustering on Timer average time

I create a dendrogram by average time per timer name. I picked k = 4 from reading the dissimilarity matrix height. Starting from the left the first group is two upload report timers, the second group are CAP timer which does not track time (CAP timer is used to track which software functionality is being used), the next three are larger data load user timer, the fourth group are faster user timers.

dissimilarity.matrix <- dist(as.matrix(timerAvg, method="euclidean"))
timer_hclust <- hclust(dissimilarity.matrix, method="ward.D") 

dendrogram_table <- as.data.frame(timer_hclust$height) 
print(dendrogram_table)

2. Association rule by Apriori on User sessions

Another interesting to do is to look at each users timer data and run an association rule algorithm on them to see strong rules. I think a typical rule would be one user action 1 leads to user action 2.

Convert dataframe to a transaction.

userTransaction <- matrix(0, nrow = 11375, ncol = 1)
for (i in 1:length(users)) {
    timerForUser <- filter(timer_user, timer_user$USERPRINCIPALS==users[i])
    ### flatten unique timer name into a single line
    uniqueTimerForUser <- unique(timerForUser$TIMERNAME);
    singleline <- paste(uniqueTimerForUser, collapse = ',')
    userTransaction[i,] <- singleline
}

## write the transaction
#trans <- as(timer_user, "transactions") does not combine user transactions 
write(userTransaction, file="C:/Users/lj015625/Desktop/DataMining Class/Final/Data/timer_basket") 
userTran<-read.transactions("C:/Users/lj015625/Desktop/DataMining Class/Final/Data/timer_basket", format="basket", sep=",")

3. KMean Clustering by user timer frequencies

We know users use a few of the timers much more than others. I want to create user profiles from user timer frequencies. First I need to create a sparse matrix of 11,375 user and 75 timers. I used cbind method to combine columns and rows. Then add frequencies from the user timer name table properties.

#Create user timer frequency matrix
timer_user_prop <- as.data.frame(table(timer_user))
dim(timer_user_prop)
## [1] 853125      3
#Combine to user timer name frequencies
userTimerSparse <- matrix(0, nrow = 11375, ncol = 75)
userTimerSparse[cbind(timer_user_prop$USERPRINCIPALS, timer_user_prop$TIMERNAME)] <- timer_user_prop$Freq;
dim(userTimerSparse)
## [1] 11375    75
userTimerSparse_df <- as.data.frame(userTimerSparse)
colnames(userTimerSparse_df) <- unique(timer_user_prop$TIMERNAME)
rownames(userTimerSparse_df) <- unique(timer_user_prop$USERPRINCIPALS)
hist(userTimerSparse_df$`CAP:MPG.RCM.POST-ACUTE-CURASPAN`)

quantile(userTimerSparse_df$`CAP:MPG.RCM.POST-ACUTE-CURASPAN`,prob = seq(0, 1, length = 6), na.rm=TRUE)
##   0%  20%  40%  60%  80% 100% 
##    0    0    0    0    0  200
hist(userTimerSparse_df$`CAP:RCM_UM_WORKLIST.01`)

quantile(userTimerSparse_df$`CAP:RCM_UM_WORKLIST.01`,prob = seq(0, 1, length = 6), na.rm=TRUE)
##   0%  20%  40%  60%  80% 100% 
##    0    0    0    0    3  178
## Optimal cluster size k
user_clusters_optimal<-kmeansruns(userTimerSparse_df, krange=3:9) #finds the "best"" K between 3 and 9
user_clusters_optimal$bestk
## [1] 3

I will test the number of clusters from 3 to 9. I will use five methods to find K: use visualization, examine Betweeness ratio (find highest) and Withinss ratio (find lowest), create Elbow method graphs from sum of betweenss and sum of withiness, use pseudo-F statistic to find the largest value, use FPC library to return best k. I end up picked K = 3.

Method 3: Use the Elbow Method from graphs of cohesiveness and distinctiveness

wss <- NULL
# for one cluster the withiness is equals to 85608131 (sum of variance on all items).
wss[1] <- (nrow(userTimerSparse_df)-1)*sum(apply(userTimerSparse_df, 2, var))
# test within ss from 2 to 9 clusters.
# elbow point at K = 3, 6
set.seed(123)
for (i in 1:9)
  wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(userTimerSparse_df, centers=i)$withinss)
## Warning: Quick-TRANSfer stage steps exceeded maximum (= 568750)
# Within Sum of Squares plot
plot(1:9, wss, type="b", xlab="Number of Clusters", ylab="Within Sum of Squares", 
     main = "Number of Clusters (k) versus Cluster Cohesiveness")

bss <- NULL
# for one cluster the betweeness is equals to 85608131 (sum of variance on all items).
bss[1] <- (nrow(userTimerSparse_df)-1)*sum(apply(userTimerSparse_df, 2, var))
# test between ss from 2 to 9 clusters.
# elbow point at K = 3, 6
set.seed(123)
for (i in 1:9) 
  bss[i] <- sum(kmeans(userTimerSparse_df, centers=i)$betweenss)
## Warning: Quick-TRANSfer stage steps exceeded maximum (= 568750)
# Between Sum of Squares plot
plot(1:9, bss, type="b", xlab="Number of Clusters",
     ylab="Between Group Sum of Squares", main = "Number of Clusters (k) versus Cluster Distinctiveness")

4. PCA and clustering by user timer frequencies

There are 75 timers in user transactions can we use PCA to reduce dimensions. Curse of dimensionality come into play. PCA helps reduce the number of variables/dimensions from the model. Can we use a few principal components then apply clustering to the user data? Variance explained graphs show first few PCA components explains most of the difference. Elbow plot picks 3 PCA components.

userTimerSparse_df_scaled <- scale(userTimerSparse_df)

Supervised Learning

So far I tried all three unsupervised learning methods. Next I want to use supervised learning method to classify slowness defined as greater than one seconds. First I want to use decision tree on data set. Next I create dummy variables from decision tree, and convert date time to a number of seconds from begin date time for logistic regression model. Next I used Nave Bayes to fit the data set.

Use caret to split training and validation sets.

set.seed(123)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(usr_timer$SLOWNESS, p = .8,list = FALSE, times = 1)
timer_train <- usr_timer[ trainIndex,]
timer_validate <- usr_timer[ -trainIndex,]

Use reusable function to print accuracy result.

getResult<- function(myModel, predictType, testData)
{
  actual <- testData$SLOWNESS
  predicted <- predict(myModel, testData, type=predictType)
  results.matrix <- confusionMatrix(predicted, actual, positive="yes")
  print(results.matrix)
}

RPart decision tree

set.seed(123)
timer_rpart <- rpart(timer_train$SLOWNESS~., method="class", parms = list(split="gini"), data=timer_train)
#plot(as.party(timer_rpart))

getResult(timer_rpart, "class", timer_validate)

10-fold cross validation

Here is the decision tree model using 10 cross validations. The decision tree shows the timer name, end date time are causing slowness. Obviously certain timer care slower just because the amount of data. Maybe certain time of the date with heavy usage causes slowness.

long_timer <- c("USR:MPG.RCM.CLINICAL_REVIEW - ADD CLINICAL REVIEW ADDENDUMS","USR:MPG.RCM.CLINICAL_REVIEW - ADD MANUAL CLINICAL REVIEW",
                "USR:MPG.RCM.CLINICAL_REVIEW - LOAD INTERQUAL CLINICAL REVIEW","USR:MPG.RCM.CLINICAL_REVIEW - MODIFY MANUAL CLINICAL REVIEW",
                "USR:MPG.RCM.CLINICAL_REVIEW - SEND CLINICAL FAX","USR:MPG.RCM.DISCHARGEREVIEWWORKLIST - GET ORDER DETAILS","USR:MPG.RCM.UTILIZATION_MANAGEMENT - LOAD COMPONENT",
                "USR:MPG.RCM.UTILIZATIONREVIEWWORKLIST - GET ORDER DETAILS")

ROC Curves

Here are results of three classification models. Notice the sensitivity are pretty low but overall accuracy is high. This is because most of timers are within 1 seconds. So it is harder to predict those small percentage of timers that are greater than 1 seconds. Kappa ratio shows Decision Tree is a OK model.

#ROC 
#Create a ROC curve
library(ROCR)

R10Fold_predict_prob<-predict(timer_10folds, type="prob", timer_validate)
R10Fold_pred = prediction(R10Fold_predict_prob[,2], timer_validate$SLOWNESS)
R10Fold_perf = performance(R10Fold_pred,"tpr", "fpr") #true pos and false pos

nb_predict_prob<-predict(timer_nb, type="raw", timer_validate)
nb_pred = prediction(nb_predict_prob[,2], timer_validate$SLOWNESS)
nb_perf = performance(nb_pred,"tpr", "fpr") #true pos and false pos

logit_predict_prob<-predict(timer_lg, type="prob", timer_validate)
## Warning in predict.lm(object, newdata, se.fit, scale = 1, type =
## ifelse(type == : prediction from a rank-deficient fit may be misleading
logit_pred = prediction(logit_predict_prob[,2], timer_validate$SLOWNESS)
logit_perf = performance(logit_pred,"tpr", "fpr") #true pos and false pos
 

# Start plotting
plot(R10Fold_perf, main="ROC Curves", col="black", lwd=2)
plot(nb_perf, add=TRUE, col="red", lwd=2)
plot(logit_perf, add=TRUE, col="green", lwd=2)
abline(a=0, b=1, lwd=2, lty=2, col="gray")
legend('bottomright', c("Decision Tree", "Naive Bayes", "Logistic Regression"), 
       lty=c(1,1), lwd=c(2.5,1), col=c("black","red","green"))

Summary

  • We can clearly see three groups of clustering users (general users, discharge nurses, utilization review nurses). PCA divides user further to regular users vs engineers and testers.
  • Apriori on user transaction data gives us typical user workflows with high confidence and lift (strong rules).
  • Particular timers, executing time can cause slowness. Classification models has high Accuracy rate but low Sensitivity rate. Picking the threshold of 1 seconds for slowness is arbitrary.
